As the classes went on, Tammy's "relationship" with Peter tempered
somewhat.  I continued to stress that the computer was a machine,
controlled by her, by me and by other programmers.  I pointed out that
I had written the program, LETTER, to help the computer help her write
stories, and that I wrote the message that she sometimes got from
the computer.

Gradually she reduced her expression of anger at the computer for error
messages, as she realized how the error messages were related to what
she had done.  Nonetheless, she continued to share credit for her
work with "Peter". "Do you want to see the stories me and Peter have
written?"  she would ask a visitor.  And she would often introduce
visitors to "Peter", using her WHO procedure.

I believe that Tammy progressed, by the end of the classes, to a more
balanced understanding of her role in relation to the computer.  By
this time, her behavior with the computer was much more matter-of-fact
and she had begun to interact very extensively with the other children
in the class.  As she came to understand the mechanical predictability
with which the computer responded to her, and as she began to take
pride in her accomplishments in story writing, "Peter" came more and
more to take on the status of a personal fantasy -- one which a child
knows is a fantasy, but persists in "playing" sometimes because
it's fun.

II. Tammy's way of working with the Computer

The strongest characteristic of Tammy's approach to working with the
computer was her need to clear the text display screen.  While many
children have a desire to clear the screen between projects, or when
bored or frustrated, Tammy exhibited this desire in an extreme way.
One of Tammy's first questions was about "how to get the words off the
screen," and learning how to accomplish this using the carriage return
was a major discovery of hers during the first class.  Once she figured
out how to do it she cleared the text display after almost every line
-- clearing it instantly after an error message without looking at the
message.  In later classes Tammy developed the habit of clearing the
text display before logging in, after logging in, after almost every
instruction that was not part of an ongoing task, and before and after
saying GOODBYE.

Tammy's habit of clearing the text display in this way interferred
significantly with her learning.  It effectively prevented her from
maintaining a continuity in what she was doing, and eliminated the
possibility of her responding to the computer's error messages.  Even
after completing a piece of work Tammy would hardly look at it:  after
I had finished helping her edit her first letter, DORIS, she swept it
off the screen without looking at the corrected version.

Tammy was able to leave several sequential lines on the screen, while
working on a specific project -- although it required a definite effort
on her part not to endulge her carriage return habit.  When working on
a drawing project, she would carefully copy all the necessary steps
into her notebook, then quickly clear the screen.

Tammy had a strong desire for completion and correctness in all her
work.  Although she might work for an hour steadily on a story, she
added to a "completed" story, however "unfinished" it might have
seemed.  Although she was quite a perfectionist by her own standards,
while working on a story, Tammy never proofread or edited a story once
she had declared it finished.  In fact, unless she noticed an error in
a particular line while typing it, or immediately after typing a
carriage return, she never went back to find an error.  Once a story
was done, it was done!  She might show it to other people, but she
rarely read it over to herself, and certainly not with a view to
analyze or correct it.  Incidents like the following were observed
several times.  lTammy was proofreading a sentence which began "ONCE
UPON TIME..."  but she read aloud, "Once upon a time..." and
continued, satisfied that her work was correct.

Tammy's attitude towards errors and towards completion of "correct"
work is also shown by her behavior in other situations.  One of her
learning disability tutors related that she would repeatedly throw out
whole pages once she had made one error -- a tactic that frustrated her
in working with a standard typewriter.  Hence in her written work she
had developed a style of writing only short pieces of one or two
"perfect" sentences.

Tammy also had a great desire for neatness in the classroom.  She took
it upon herself to collect and put away pens, notebooks, and other
items which had been left out by the children.  She would also remind
others regularly to put their things away.

In her pre-LOGO interview, Tammy showed the same kind of strategy, when
trying to arrange a series of permutations of a set of colored blocks.
The task was to create as many different arrangements of the blocks as
possible.  After having done a few, Tammy swept the old ones away,
clearing the table -- thus making it impossible for her to know whether
the next one was different or not.  When the interviewer re-established
all Tammy's old arrangements, she made one more, and then compulsively
swept them all away again.

In her work with the computer, Tammy quickly established a set of
conditions about what she could and couldn't do, and adhered to these
with little change through the classes.  Tammy could do the
folowing:  LOGIN "TAMMY; LET LETTER (to get her letter writing
procedure); start, write and end a letter; run a letter or a drawing
procedure by typing its name; and type the word GOODBYE.  Things she
couldn't or wouldn't do on her own included:  writing a procedure;
editing a procedure or a story; saving a procedure, by writing a file;
reading a file; and using the lineprinter.  These things, part of her
daily routine, wre done for her by me.

Since I wanted Tammy's work with the computer to be simple and
straightforward, with as few stumbling blocks as possible, I fell into
the habit of doing some of these things for Tammy, thinking that she
would gradually take over some of the functions as her work continued.
I found that it was very important for Tammy to keep the boundary
between what she would and wouldn't do, very firm.  Towards the end of
the classes, I made an effort to get her to use the lineprinter on her
own, showing her the PRINTON command, and showing her how to make
multiple copies of a story by using REPEAT.  Tammy objected to this
strongly, but agreed to do some of it, if I would share the work
with her.  I think that she would have eventually learned these
commands, and have attained a greater measure of independence in her
computer use.

Tammy did develop one way of editing stories.  If she made a mistake
early in a story she could start again by typing END, and clearing the
screen.  Typing LET LETTER again would clear out her workspace and
allow her to begin her story again.  Interestingly, when she did this,
she almost always typed an identical sentence to the one she had typed
before -- without any printed reference -- sometimes complete with the
error that had forced her to start over in the first place.  In such
cases she would stop and go through the whole process again until she
got it right.

Another characteristic of Tammy's working style was that she took a
long time to settle down to productive work.  She usually came to class
later than the other students, and wandered around a bit before
deciding what to do.  Once started on a story, she often made a lot of
mistakes on the first line -- requiring her to start the whole story
over again.  Once past the first line, however, she typ8ically finished
a story without any more false starts.  Her problem with starting was
reflected in a rush at the end of the class.  Since Tammy placed a
premium on completed work, she often found it necessary to stay after
class to finish up.

