I have tried to speculate about the reasons why Tammy was able to
accomplish so much in the area of writing in the LOGO classes, while
she has been unable to accomplish much writing in either her regular
classes or with her language tutors.  After consulting with her
teachers, I think I have some insights about how this came about.

Tammy is a fanatic about complete work without errors.  When an error
occurs in Tammy's normal work, she tears up the paper and throws it
away.  Since she never examines her errors, or tries to learn from
them, errors are seen by her as a total disaster.  Using the computer,
she was able to rubout many errors as they occurred without destroying
all her work up to that point.  In this way she could be satisfied with
her finished product.  Once she declared herself "finished" she never
looked back to see if there were any other errors.

The nicely typed computer output had a "professional" quality that
looked more polished than anyone else's work.  In addition, she could
have as many copies as she wanted at no extra effort -- which could
bring her positive attention from friends, family, and several
different teachers, all in the same day.

In accordance with her abhorance of "errors", Tammy may feel extremely
sensitive to any "correction" of her work whether direct or implied.  I
offered no correctino or criticism of Tammy's work, and confined my
assistance to answering her questions about spelling and
punctuation.  In this case, Tammy knew that her work would not be
criticized.  Therefore, since it looked "correct", even outstanding,
and since Tammy had worked hard to get it "correct", Tammy assumed that
it was "correct, and was very proud of it.

Tammy felt that her work was unique among the kids in the computer
classes.  Just as only Tammy could use the computer she called "PTER",
only Tammy could use the LETTER procedure to write stories.  Thus Tammy
could feel that her work was at least as good as the other students'
work.  Tammy rearely has had the opportunity to feel taht way about her
work.

In a meeting held after the end of computer classes, Tammy's English
teacher said that Tammy has recently been making a significant effort
to complete assignments and turn in work.  She said that Tammy's
computer stories were the first completed work that Tammy had given her
this year.

