V. Tammy's Social Behavior with Adults and Children

Just as Tammy's "relationship" with the computer was of the utmost
importance to her, she also palced a high premium on her personal
relationships with the people around her.  At first Tammy seemed to
have a great deal of sensitivity about being "watched" by adults in the
classroom which relaxed a bit as the classes went on.  She was
particularly concerned about observers who took notes, and she would
occassionally ask them what they were writing about.  Tammy made a
point of introducing herself to all the visitors who came at different
times to observe the classes, and of establishing a definite
relationship with any who came more than once.

At times, Tammy could be quite manipulative -- especially when she
wanted help.  She could be loud and insistent calling across the room
for assistance, and a few minutes later rebuke another child for
"interrupting".  She often corrected other people's behavior, saying
that some action, or omission was "rude", or "sloppy".  This was
usually done in a somewhat cherrful, "motherly" tone that had only a
slight undercurrent of hostility.

Tammy insisted that she be noticed.  When she came to class late, she
would often be singing or shouting loudly in an impressively powerful
voice, as she walked in the door.  If a visitor was present, she would
quite down suddenly in embarrassment. Throughout the class period she
would call loudly across the room to a teacher, visitor or a classmate.

In her relations with her classmates, Tammy adopted a "breezy,"
somewhat teasing style, characterized by a cheerful good humor.
Occasionally this "breeziness" got out of control, and became
disruptive and rowdy, including chases around the room, hitting and
hair-pulling.  At such times, Tammy had a very difficult time settling
back into appropriate class behavior.

At other times -- especially with visitors present -- Tammy would be
extremely quitet, polite and demure.  It was as if she had two sets of
rules -- one for serious behavior in public -- the other for playful
behavior in private.  As the classes went on, it was clear that Tammy
considered the LOGO classroom as a "private" place, where she was among
friends and could be her playful self.

At first Tammy was "tolerated", somewhat sceptically by the other kids.
 Gradually, Holly and David got quite involved with her playfulness,
and cherrful bantring.  Most of the time they seemed to enjoy the
distraction she provided, and allowed her to provide an excuse for
letting their own playfulness emerge on occasion.  A>J> remained aloof.

Holly became quite "protective" of Tammy, sticking up for her on
occasion, as well as helping her with her work from time to time.
Tammy gradually came to consult Holy frequently about spelling and
punctuation.  Holly spent a lot of one class period helping Tammy type
a turtle procedure, and showing her how to use the SPIN command.

Tammy took a lot of interest in Holly and David as a "couple", teasing
them regularly about their friendship.  She wrote their "relationship"
into her story, HOLLY, and spent a good deal of one class period
watching them play dynaturtle games together -- commenting regularly,
not on their dynaturtle strategies, but on their personal interchanges.

Holly's interest in Tammy was evidenced outside of LOGO classes as
well.  One of Tammy's classroom teachers reported that she had moved
her seat in class to be near Holly and her group of friends.  In
becoming accepted by them, she had moved from virtual "isolation into
the core of the class, socially."  Her teacher attributed this to the
relationship Tammy developed during the LOGO classes and to the feeling
of success she has had with her computer work.
